<section id="fs-idp133535040" class="free-response">
<title>Free Response</title>
<exercise id="fs-idp2026496">
<problem id="fs-idm22060848"><para id="fs-idp38761008">Describe the hypothesized steps in the origin of eukaryotic cells.</para></problem>
<solution id="fs-idp101876784"><label/>
<para id="fs-idp22067248">Eukaryotic cells arose through endosymbiotic events that gave rise to the energy-producing organelles within the eukaryotic cells such as mitochondria and chloroplasts. The nuclear genome of eukaryotes is related most closely to the Archaea, so it may have been an early archaean that engulfed a bacterial cell that evolved into a mitochondrion. Mitochondria appear to have originated from an alpha-proteobacterium, whereas chloroplasts originated as a cyanobacterium. There is also evidence of secondary endosymbiotic events. Other cell components may also have resulted from endosymbiotic events.</para></solution>
</exercise>
